The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Briefs
                                                                                                                       7                                                                                                        
	Madrid: Real Madrid will present Jose Mourinho as coach on Monday after agreeing an undisclosed compensation deal with Inter Milan, the Spanish club said in a statement on Friday. The two club presidents held a meeting in Milan on Friday to thrash out details of the package that will free Mourinho to leave Inter and join the nine-time European champions after a treble-winning season in Italy. No details of the deal were available but Spanish and Italian media reported that Inter would receive eight million euros ($9.80 million).      
	Euro 16 hosts  
	Geneva: After a personal appeal by President Nicolas Sarkozy, France defeated Turkey and Italy Friday for the right to host footballs European Championship in 2016. Uefas ruling executive voted 7-6 for the French bid over Turkey after Italy was eliminated in a first-round points ballot. France will be the first country to host the championship three times.  
	Jeev tied 113th   
	Fort Worth (US): Jeev Milkha Singh was at the wrong end of the leaderboard after carding a three-over 73 in the opening round to be at the 113th spot in the Crowne Plaza Invitational.   
	Strong start   
	Madrid: Shiv Kapur carded a three-under 69 in the opening round to lie tied 27th in the Madrid Masters golf meet but Jyoti Randhawa is certain to miss the cut after a horrendous eight-over 80. S.S.P. Chowrasia, was at the tied 62nd spot after his round of one-under 71.  
	Hockey meeting  
	New Delhi: Undeterred by the revival of the K.P.S. Gill-led Indian Hockey Federation, Hockey India Friday convened its special general council meeting here on June 14. In a communication to all its member units, HI asked one male and one female representative each from the affiliated bodies to attend the meeting.  
	Medals assured  
	New Delhi: Despite the shock quarter final defeat of former world championship silver medallist N. Usha on Friday, Indias assured medal tally swelled to eight in the Asian Womens Boxing Championship in Astana, Kazakhstan.  
	Moscow meet  
	New Delhi: The Indian mens team squandered an early lead after Sharath Kamal won the opening tie to go down 2-3 to Serbia while their women counterparts snatched a hard-fought 3-2 win over Israel in the second round of the World Table Tennis Team Championships in Moscow on Friday.      
	Calcutta: Howrah Union entered the semi-final of the under-19 all-India inter-academy meet in Bangalore, according to information received here.    
	Brief Scores: Gush CA Delhi 154 (Zamir Ahmed Ansari 3/25, Himanshu Singh 3/27). Howrah Union 158/3(Zamir Ahmed Ansari 91 n.o.). Howrah Union won by 7 wkts.                                                                                                                                                      
